  "prompt": "What is the difference between transistor and transformer?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between transistors and transformers:\n\nTransistor:\n1. Electronic semiconductor device\n2. Used for amplifying or switching electronic signals\n3. Consists of three terminals (emitter, base, collector)\n4. Actively controls electrical current\n5. Used in electronic circuits for signal processing\n6. Operates with low power\n7. Can be made very small\n8. Requires electrical power to function\n9. Primarily used in electronic devices like computers, radios, etc.\n\nTransformer:\n1. Electrical passive device\n2. Used for transferring electrical energy between circuits\n3. Consists of primary and secondary windings\n4. Transfers electrical energy through electromagnetic induction\n5. Changes voltage levels between different circuits\n6. Works with alternating current (AC)\n7. Typically larger in physical size\n8. Does not require additional power to operate\n9. Primarily used in power transmission and distribution systems\n10. Can step voltage up or down\n\nMain difference: A transistor actively controls electrical signals, while a transformer passively transfers electrical energy between circuits through electromagnetic induction.",
